ve this|write this down|capture this|log this|record this\"\n\nfor sess in \"${sessions[@]}\"; do\n  result=$(rg -n -i \"$pattern\" \"$base/$sess\" 2>/dev/null)\n  if [[ -n \"$result\" ]]; then\n    echo \"=== $sess ===\"\n    echo \"$result\"\n    echo \"\"\n  fi\ndone","timeout":60}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":41558,"output":1093,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42651,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1776031263390}}
{"type":"message","id":"15696e87","parentId":"61e22492","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:01:04.438Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_1a497fc8-d868-4c93-b4e5-2a16c2ead65d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"we are constantly compacting our sessions, do you agree?\\n2026-03-25T08:19:49.754Z\\nPre-compaction memory flush. Store durable memories only in memory/2026-03-25.md (create memory/ if needed). Treat workspace bootstrap/reference files such as MEMORY.md, SOUL.md, TOOLS.md, and AGENTS.md as read-only during this flush; never overwrite, replace, or edit them. If memory/2026-03-25.md already exists, APPEND new content only and do not overwrite existing entries. Do NOT create timestamped variant files (e.g., 2026-03-25-HHMM.md); always use the canonical 2026-03-25.md filename. If nothing to store, reply with NO_REPLY.\\nCurrent time: Wednesday, March 25th, 2026 — 10:19 AM (Africa/Johannesburg) / 2026-03-25 08:19 UTC\\n2026-03-25T08:20:31.493Z\\nSystem: [2026-03-25 10:17:10 GMT+2] [Post-compaction context refresh]\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Session was just compacted. The conversation summary above is a hint, NOT a substitute for your startup sequence. Run your Session Startup sequence — read the required files before responding to the user.\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Critical rules from AGENTS.md:\\nSystem: \\nSystem: ## Session Startup\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Before doing anything else:\\nSystem: \\nSystem: 1. Read `SOUL.md` — this is who you are\\nSystem: 2. Read `USER.md` — this is who you're helping\\nSystem: 3. Read `memory/2026-03-25.md` (today + yesterday) for recent context\\nSystem: 4. **If in MAIN SESSION** (direct chat with your human): Also read `MEMORY.md`\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Don't ask permission. Just do it.\\nSystem: \\nSystem: ## Red Lines\\nSystem: \\nSystem: - Don't exfiltrate private data. Ever.\\nSystem: - Don't run destructive commands without asking.\\nSystem: - `trash` > `rm` (recoverable beats gone forever)\\nSystem: - When in doubt, ask.\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Current time: Wednesday, March 25th, 2026 — 10:17 AM (Africa/Johannesburg) / 2026-03-25 08:17 UTC\\n\\nSender (untrusted metadata):\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"label\\\": \\\"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\\\",\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"gateway-client\\\",\\n  \\\"name\\\": \\\"openclaw-tui\\\",\\n  \\\"username\\\": \\\"openclaw-tui\\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\n[Wed 2026-03-25 10:19 GMT+2] I have added screenshots to my Onedrive folder today. They are of Yosef and my posts. But they may be tricky to understand. Here is what you need to know:\\n1. Because the threads are long, some had to be capture in multiple screenshots.\\n2. They are always reacting to a Nava post. The post should exist in the corpora but might not. If it does, great, but if not, add it.\\n3. The older posts are less significant as my writing style has changed over time. The newer posts are what matters.\\n4. Below is an unposted text that I wrote for Yosef.\\n5. I know this may get confusing so ask questions if needed. Use Gemma effectively.\\n----------------------------\\nBack when I was a healthcare exec, I was often frustrated by the model used by standard recruitment agencies. It felt like a transactional volume game, moving names across a board without much regard for the actual operational friction left behind. One of those \\\"standard\\\" realities I tried too hard not to think about was the 90-day benefits waiting period.\\n\\nOn a spreadsheet, that waiting period is a perfectly logical shield for the P&L. It’s a hedge against the high cost of benefits for transient staff who might not make it past orientation. But from the administrator's chair, it’s easy to overlook how that policy creates a \\\"180-day pincer movement\\\" of stress for the exact clinicians you are trying to recruit.\\n\\nWhen an elite clinical leader gives a 90-day notice at their current facility, followed by a 90-day wait at yours, they are looking at six months of vulnerability. In many cases, we are effectively asking high-level professionals to pay a $7,500 \\\"entry fee\\\" in COBRA premiums just for the privilege of joining our teams. For a clinician with a family, it’s not just an onboarding delay but a massive personal risk that most candidates don't have the leverage to negotiate past.\\n\\nThe goal isn’t to abolish the waiting period for everyone (although, from the clinician side, there is a strong case for that). When we started Nava, there were a lot of issues we wanted to fix in the recruitment world: the upfront fees, the lack of recruiter investment, and the fact that agents were too focused on volume. Flip the contract, collect the fees, back to the job boards, repeat.\\n\\nOne issue particularly close to my heart was making sure candidates aren't just keywords on a page, but recognized as humans in unique circumstances. Most HR departments simply don’t have the bandwidth to invest time in every single applicant's personal situation, and they end up trapped by rigid policies. We thought there had to be a better way. Not only to make candidates feel seen, but also one that gives leaders the real-world confidence to stop managing by policy and start leading by people. Because when you've done the work to ensure a candidate is a true long-term fit, that 90-day \\\"shield\\\" stops being a protection and starts being the only thing standing in the way of a stable unit.\\n\\nWe get it. As a healthcare facility, you can’t afford to trust that every candidate will not screw you over. But you don’t have to. You can trust us.\\n2026-03-25T08:21:39.193Z\\nSystem: [2026-03-25 10:20:49 GMT+2] [Post-compaction context refresh]\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Session was just compacted. The conversation summary above is a hint, NOT a substitute for your startup sequence. Run your Session Startup sequence — read the required files before responding to the user.\\nSystem: \\nSystem: Critical rules from AGENTS.md:\\nSystem: \\nSystem: ## Session Startup\\nSystem: \\nSys